%N A389638 Numbers k such that 2*k can be represented as the sum of four (not necessarily distinct) squares of primes.
%C A389638 This sequence is motivated by the Goldbach conjecture and Lagrange's four-square theorem.
%C A389638 The case of distinct squares is in A389640.
%H A389638 Paolo Xausa, <a href="/A389638/b389638.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A389638 Angel V. Kumchev and Lilu Zhao, <a href="https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.1503.01799">Sums of four squares of primes</a>, arXiv:1503.01799 [math.NT], Mar 2015.
%H A389638 Jianya Liu and Ming-Chit Liu, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1006/jnth.1999.2500">Representation of Even Integers as Sums of Squares of Primes and Powers of 2</a>, Journal of Number Theory, Volume 83, Issue 2, August 2000, Pages 202-225.
%H A389638 Jianya Liu, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1093/qmath/hag028">On Lagrange's Theorem with Prime Variables</a>, Quarterly Journal of Mathematics, vol. 54, no. 4, pp. 453-462, Dec. 2003.
%e A389638 k =  8 ->  16 = 2^2 + 2^2 + 2^2 + 2^2.
%e A389638 k = 74 -> 148 = 3^2 + 3^2 + 3^2 + 11^2 = 5^2 + 5^2 + 7^2 + 7^2.
%e A389638 k = 98 -> 196 = 3^2 + 3^2 + 3^2 + 13^2 = 5^2 + 5^2 + 5^2 + 11^2 = 7^2 + 7^2 + 7^2 + 7^2.
%p A389638 A389638List := proc(lim) local PS, i, j, k, l; PS:= [seq(ithprime(i)^2, i=1..lim+1)]: sort(convert(select(t -> t::integer and t <= PS[lim]/2, {seq(seq(seq(seq((PS[i] + PS[j] + PS[k] + PS[l])/2, l=k..lim), k=j..lim), j=i..lim), i=1..lim)}), list)); end: A389638List(10);
%t A389638 A389638list[pmax_] := With[{ps = Prime[Range[pmax + 1]]^2}, Select[Union[Flatten[Table[ps[[i]] + ps[[j]] + ps[[k]] + ps[[l]], {i, pmax}, {j, i, pmax}, {k, j, pmax}, {l, k, pmax}]]], IntegerQ[#/2] && # <= Last[ps] &]/2];
%t A389638 A389638list[8] (* _Paolo Xausa_, Oct 25 2025 *)
